04818nam a22008655i 9780814749135DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20062006nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147491357 a10.18574/nyu/9780814749135.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)548039  a(OCoLC)779828158  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0360002bisacsh1 aKersten, Andrew E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLabor's Home Front :bThe American Federation of Labor during World War II /cAndrew E. Kersten. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource :b28 black and white illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: Labor’s Grave Hour -- t1 The Politics of “Equality of Sacrifice”: The AFL and Wartime Labor Relations -- t2 Putting the Shackles on Labor: The AFL and the Fight Against the Open Shop -- t3 Building Ships for Democracy: The AFL, the Boilermakers, and Wartime Racial Justice in Portland and Providence -- t4 “Under the Stress of Necessity”: Women and the AFL -- t5 Union Against Union: The AFL and CIO Rivalry -- t6 Death in the Factories: Worker Safety and the AFL -- t7 Planning America’s Future: The AFL and Postwar Planning -- tEpilogue: Labor’s Moment -- tNotes -- tA Note on Sources -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of the oldest, strongest, and largest labor organizations in the U.S., the American Federation of Labor (AFL) had 4 million members in over 20,000 union locals during World War II. The AFL played a key role in wartime production and was a major actor in the contentious relationship between the state, organized labor, and the working class in the 1940s. The war years are pivotal in the history of American labor, but books on the AFL’s experiences are scant, with far more on the radical Congress of Industrial Unions (CIO).Andrew E. Kersten closes this gap with Labor’s Home Front, challenging us to reconsider the AFL and its influence on twentieth-century history. Kersten details the union's contributions to wartime labor relations, its opposition to the open shop movement, divided support for fair employment and equity for women and African American workers, its constant battles with the CIO, and its significant efforts to reshape American society, economics, and politics after the war. Throughout, Kersten frames his narrative with an original, central theme: that despite its conservative nature, the AFL was dramatically transformed during World War II, becoming a more powerful progressive force that pushed for liberal change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aLabor policyzUnited Statesy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  a1940s.  aAmerican.  aFederation.  aactor.  abetween.  aclass.  acontentious.  ahistory.  alabor.  amajor.  aorganized.  aplayed.  aproduction.  arelationship.  arole.  astate.  awartime.  awhich.  aworking.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814749135.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814749135423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814749135/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK